Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(diced into small pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 1cm sized chunks. Trim the @green beans{80%g} and chop into thirds. Trim the @courgette{1}, quarter lengthways and cut into 1cm chunks. Chop the @paneer{250%g} into 2cm chunks.

Pour the cold water for the rice (@water for the rice{300%ml}) into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{0.25%tsp}, cover with the lid and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to its lowest setting. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large frying pan{} over medium heat and add the onion and @paneer{250%g}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and starting to turn golden, ~{6-7%minutes}. Add the pepper to the pan with the onions, stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the @tandoori masala spice{1%tbsp} and cook for ~{30%seconds}. Now add the @ginger puree{1/2%tsp}, garlic and @tomato puree{30%g}, stir and cook for another ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the water for the curry (@water for the curry{150%ml}), the @creme fraiche{75%g}, @coconut milk{200%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}. Bring to the boil, stirring to combine, then reduce the heat to medium, stir in the green beans and courgette, cover the pan with a #lid{} (or some #tin foil{}) and simmer until the veg are almost tender, ~{8-9%minutes}. Remove the lid and allow to simmer until the mixture has thickened and the veggies are cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). When the curry is cooked, season to taste with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed, add the @?red chilli flakes{1%tsp} (if you want a bit of spice) and stir in half the coriander.

> Add a splash of water if it's looking a bit thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}. Serve the rice in #bowls{} topped with plenty of veggie tikka and the remaining coriander. Enjoy!

> Variation: If you've decided to add paneer to your meal, pop the cubes into the pan with the onions and fry until golden brown.